      "qa": "问题 & 回答\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nThe decline is cost-driven, not revenue-driven:\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nRevenue flat at $38M (traffic -8% offset by price +5%)\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nCOGS rose from 31% to 35% of revenue (+$1.5M impact)\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nLabor rose from 28% to 32% of revenue (+$1.5M impact)\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nCombined: ~$3M cost increase explains the $1.1M EBITDA decline (partially offset by price increases)\nQ1: What is the primary driver of the profitability decline?\nThis is a classic cost squeeze case. Revenue is masking the problem because price increases offset traffic declines. But costs are rising faster than prices.\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\nRecommend closing 5-7 underperforming stores:\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\n1. All 5 downtown stores (negative EBITDA, structural traffic problem from remote work)\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\n2. 2-3 worst-performing older strip mall locations (below $600K revenue, sub-5% margin)\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\n3. Keep remaining 37-40 stores and invest in top performers\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\nClosing 7 stores saves ~$400K in losses + frees capital for reinvestment\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\nSeverance and lease termination costs: ~$200-300K one-time\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\nNet benefit: $400K annual savings after Year 1\nQ2: Which stores should be closed?\nClosing underperforming stores is the single highest-impact action. Every dollar lost in a bad store could be invested in a good one.\nQ3: How should the menu be optimized?\nEliminate sandwiches: saves labor, simplifies operations, removes lowest-margin product\nQ3: How should the menu be optimized?\nExpand coffee/beverage program: add specialty drinks, loyalty program for daily visits\nQ3: How should the menu be optimized?\nStreamline custom cakes: limit to 5 core designs instead of fully custom, reduce decorator labor\nQ3: How should the menu be optimized?\nIntroduce \"bakery box\" bundles: curated assortment at fixed price point to increase average ticket\nQ3: How should the menu be optimized?\nMenu optimization should follow the 80/20 rule: focus on the products (pastries + coffee) that drive 50% of revenue with the highest margins.\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nCentralized procurement: negotiate volume discounts across 45 locations\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nSupplier diversification: reduce dependency on single butter/sugar suppliers\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nRecipe reformulation: test alternative ingredients without quality loss (e.g., blend butter with high-quality margarine in select items)\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nMenu pricing: implement quarterly price reviews tied to ingredient cost index\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nWaste reduction: standardize portion sizes, improve inventory management to reduce spoilage (bakeries typically waste 8-12% of ingredients)\nQ4: How can the client address rising ingredient costs?\nRecommendation\nProfitability decline is cost-driven: COGS (+4pp) and labor (+4pp) squeezed margins by $3M. Recommend a three-pronged turnaround: (1) close 5-7 underperforming stores, (2) optimize menu by eliminating sandwiches and expanding coffee, (3) centralize procurement to reduce ingredient costs. Revenue: $38M (flat), EBITDA: $4.6M (down from $5.7M) COGS: 31% → 35% (+$1.5M); Labor: 28% → 32% (+$1.5M) Close 5-7 stores: +$400K annual savings Menu optimization (drop sandwiches, expand coffee): +$300-500K margin improvement Procurement centralization: 2-3% COGS reduction = +$250-400K Store closures may affect brand perception and employee morale Eliminating sandwiches may lose some lunch traffic (but these customers are low-value) Ingredient inflation could continue if commodity markets remain volatile Competitor Crumbl Cookies expanding aggressively in Southeast Conduct store-by-store profitability review for closure decisions Pilot coffee-focused menu in 3 top-performing stores Issue RFP for centralized ingredient procurement Develop 12-month implementation roadmap with quarterly milestones ──────────────────────────────────────────────────\n优先实施高影响、低风险的举措（Quick Wins）\n建立定期评估机制，跟踪措施效果\n预留应急方案应对潜在风险\nRisks & Next Steps\nRisk 1: 实施过程中可能遇到的阻力和应对方案\nRisk 2: 市场或竞争环境变化带来的不确定性\nRisk 3: 内部资源和能力是否足以支撑执行",
      "tips": "Case难点分析\n需要在有限信息下快速建立分析框架，避免遗漏关键维度\nExhibit数据解读需要同时关注绝对值和相对变化（%），避免被大数字误导\n计算环节需要在压力下保持准确性，同时展示结构化的计算过程\n推荐方案需要权衡短期和长期影响，不能只考虑单一维度\n得分亮点\n框架搭建时体现\"假设驱动\"思维——先说\"我认为最可能的问题是...\"再展开验证\n数据分析时主动计算关键比率和趋势，不需要面试官提示\n推荐方案时给出具体的量化影响估算，而非泛泛而谈\n主动提及风险和缓解措施，展示全面的商业思维\n面试技巧\n开场2分钟内搭好框架并与面试官确认，不要花太多时间在框架上\n计算时边写边说，让面试官了解你的思路，即使算错也能获得部分分数\nExhibit分析采用\"总结-细节-洞察\"三步法：先说总体趋势，再看细分项，最后给出洞察\n推荐环节使用\"金字塔结构\"：先给结论，再说支撑理由，最后提风险和下一步\n面试官视角：区分\"好\"和\"优秀\"候选人的关键在于——是否能主动提出面试官没有问的、但对决策有重要影响的因素。",
