      "framework": "Customer Segmentation\nDemographics: Core users are 25-45 year old professionals in urban/suburban areas. Mental health is the fastest-growing service (40% of visits)\nCustomer Segmentation\nUse cases: Convenience seekers (70%) vs access-constrained (rural, mobility-limited) (30%)\nCustomer Segmentation\nPayer mix: 45% insurance, 35% self-pay, 20% employer-sponsored\nCustomer Segmentation\nRetention: Mental health patients retain 2.5x better than primary care (subscription model vs episodic)\nCustomer Acquisition\nPaid digital: Google/Meta ads — CAC $85, declining efficiency as competitors bid up healthcare keywords\nCustomer Acquisition\nInsurance partnerships: In-network with 5 major insurers. Each partnership adds 30-50K users at near-zero CAC\nCustomer Acquisition\nEmployer channel: B2B2C through employer health benefits. 200 employers, 150K users. CAC effectively $15/user\nCustomer Acquisition\nReferrals: Current referral rate 8%. Each referral user has 2x retention vs paid acquisition\nCustomer Acquisition\nContent/SEO: Health content driving 2M monthly visits, converting at 1.2%. Low CAC but slow to scale\nUnit Economics\nRevenue per user per month: $12.50 (blended across services)\nUnit Economics\nGross margin: 45% (physician costs are the largest expense at ~40% of revenue)\nUnit Economics\nContribution margin per user: $5.60/month after variable costs\nUnit Economics\nPayback period on CAC: 15 months (paid channels) vs 3 months (employer/insurance)\nUnit Economics\nMental health subscription: $150/month, 70% gross margin — best unit economics\nGeographic Expansion\nState licensing: Each new state requires 6-12 months for medical licensing. Texas, Florida, California = 50M+ addressable population\nGeographic Expansion\nInterstate Medical Licensure Compact: 40 states participate — accelerates multi-state licensing\nGeographic Expansion\nPriority markets: Florida (22M pop, high elderly population), Texas (30M, underserved rural areas), California (39M, tech-savvy)\nGeographic Expansion\nInternational: UK and Canada have regulatory frameworks for telehealth — longer-term opportunity\nGeographic Expansion",
